le class, the poor, and democracy in Thailand -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aDrawing on critical theory and post-modernism, this book argues for a new strategy for writing about the social and cultural experiences of living in modern Southeast Asian states. Contributors -- many of whom work in universities in the region -- question the processes of cultural transformation under conditions of globalization and rapid economic and political change. By paying attention to the specificity of what is taking place in the particular state, the book questions the conventional narratives of developmentalism and state-sponsored national peace as they are understood in Southeast Asia, and shows how such understanding can be made and unmade.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aMass mediaxPolitical aspectszSoutheast Asia. 0aMass mediaxSocial aspectszSoutheast Asia. 0aNationalismzSoutheast Asia. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh1 aAng, Ien, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBerger, Mark T., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCarruthers, Ashley, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChoy, Lee Weng, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHarper, T.N., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHeng, Russell H.-K., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLangenbach, Ray, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOckey, James, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRoces, Marian Pastor, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSouchou, Yao, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/voca